# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: extinction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 2 Esdras forms a part of the canon of Scripture in the Ethiopian Orthodox Church (an Oriental Orthodoxy body), though it is reckoned among the apocrypha by Catholics and Protestants.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Within Eastern Orthodoxy it forms a part of the canon although its usage varies by different traditions.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 2 Esdras was translated by Jerome as part of the Vulgate, though he placed it in an appendix.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] As with 1 Esdras, some confusion exists about the numbering of this book.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The Vulgate of Jerome includes only a single book of Ezra, but in the Clementine Vulgate, 1, 2, 3 and 4 Esdras are separate books.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Protestant writers, after the Geneva Bible, called 1 and 2 Esdras of the Vulgate Ezra and Nehemiah, respectively, and called 3 and 4 Esdras of the Vulgate 1 Esdras and 2 Esdras, respectively.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] These then became the common names for these books in English Bibles.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Medieval Latin manuscripts denoted it 4 Esdras, which to this day is the name used for chapters 3–14 in modern critical editions, which are typically in Latin, the language of its most complete exemplars.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] It appears in the Appendix to the Old Testament in the Slavonic Bible, where it is called 3 Esdras, and the Georgian Orthodox Bible numbers it 3 Ezra.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] This text is sometimes also known as Apocalypse of Ezra — chapters 3–14 known as the Jewish Apocalypse of Ezra or 4 Ezra; in modern critical editions, chapters 1–2 are named as 5 Ezra, and chapters 15–16 as 6 Ezra.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Bogaert speculates that the "fourth book of Ezra" referred to by Jerome most likely corresponds to modern 5 Ezra and 6 Ezra combined, and notes a number of Latin manuscripts where these chapters are together in an appendix.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The first two chapters of 2 Esdras are found only in the Latin version of the book, and are called 5 Ezra by scholars.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] They are considered by most scholars to be Christian in origin; they assert God's rejection of the Jews and describe a vision of the Son of God.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] These are generally considered to be late additions (possibly third century) to the work.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Chapters 3–14, or the great bulk of 2 Esdras, is a Jewish apocalypse, also sometimes known as 4 Ezra or the Jewish Apocalypse of Ezra.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The latter name should not be confused with a later work called the *Greek Apocalypse of Ezra*.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The Ethiopian Church considers 4 Ezra to be canonical, written during the Babylonian captivity, and calls it Izra Sutuel (ዕዝራ ሱቱኤል).
[src:extinction/2-esdras] It was also often cited by the Fathers of the Church.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] In the Eastern Armenian tradition, it is called 3 Ezra.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] It was written in the late first century CE following the destruction of the Second Temple.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Among Greek Fathers of the Church, 4 Ezra is generally cited as Προφήτης Ἔσδρας *Prophetes Esdras* ("The Prophet Ezra") or Ἀποκάλυψις Ἔσδρα *Apokalupsis Esdra* ("Apocalypse of Ezra").
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Most scholars agree that 4 Ezra was composed in Hebrew, which was translated into Greek, and then to Latin, Armenian, Ethiopian, and Georgian, but the Hebrew and Greek editions have been lost.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Slightly differing Latin, Syriac, Arabic, Ethiopic, Georgian, and Armenian translations have survived in their entirety; the Greek version can be reconstructed, though without absolute certainty, from these different translations, while the Hebrew text remains more elusive.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The modern Slavonic version is translated from the Latin.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 4 Ezra consists of seven visions of Ezra the scribe.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The first vision takes place as Ezra is still in Babylon.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] He asks God how Israel can be kept in misery if God is just.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The archangel Uriel is sent to answer the question, responding that God's ways cannot be understood by the human mind.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Soon, however, the end would come, and God's justice would be made manifest.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Similarly, in the second vision, Ezra asks why Israel was delivered up to the Babylonians, and is again told that man cannot understand this and that the end is near.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] In the third vision, Ezra asks why Israel does not possess the world.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Uriel responds that the current state is a period of transition.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Here follows a description of the fate of evil-doers and the righteous.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Ezra asks whether the righteous may intercede for the unrighteous on Judgment Day, but is told that "Judgment Day is final".
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The next three visions are more symbolic in nature.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The fourth is of a woman mourning for her only son.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] She is transformed into a city when she hears of the desolation of Zion.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Uriel says that the woman is a symbol of Zion.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The fifth vision concerns an eagle with three heads and 20 wings (12 large wings and eight smaller wings "over against them").
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The eagle is rebuked by a lion and then burned.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The explanation of this vision is that the eagle refers to the fourth kingdom of the vision of Daniel, with the wings and heads as rulers.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The final scene is the triumph of the Messiah over the empire.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The sixth vision is of a man, representing the Messiah, who breathes fire on a crowd that is attacking him.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] This man then turns to another peaceful multitude, which accepts him.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Finally, a vision of the restoration of scripture is related.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] God appears to Ezra in a bush and commands him to restore the Law.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Ezra gathers five scribes and begins to dictate.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] After 40 days, he has produced 204 books, including 70 works to be published last.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The "seventy" might refer to the Septuagint, most of the apocrypha, or the lost books that are described in the Bible.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] But it is more probable that the number is just symbolic.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Almost all Latin editions of the text have a large lacuna of 70 verses between 7:35 and 7:36 that is missing because they trace their common origin to one early manuscript, *Codex Sangermanensis I*, from which an entire page had been cut out very early in its history.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] In 1875 Robert Lubbock Bensly published the lost verses and in 1895 M.R.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] James oversaw a critical edition from Bensly's notes restoring the lost verses from the complete text found in the *Codex Colbertinus*; this edition is used in the Stuttgart edition of the Vulgate.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] For more information, see the article *Codex Sangermanensis I*.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Second Esdras turns around a radical spiritual conversion of Ezra in a vision, where he stops to comfort a sobbing woman who turns instantly into a great city (2 Esd.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The following verses (10:28–59) reveal that Ezra had a vision of the heavenly Jerusalem, the true city of Zion, which the angel of the Lord invites him to explore.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The last two chapters, also called 6 Ezra by scholars, and found in the Latin, but not in the Eastern texts, predict wars and rebuke sinners.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Many assume that they probably date from a much later period (perhaps late third century) and may be Christian in origin; though not certain, they possibly were added at the same time as the first two chapters of the Latin version.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] They likely are Jewish in origin, however; 15:57–59 have been found in Greek, which most scholars agree was translated from a Hebrew original.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The main body of the book appears to be written for consolation in a period of great distress (one scholarly hypothesis is that it dates to Titus' destruction of the Second Temple in 70 CE).
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The author seeks answers, similar to Job's quest for understanding the meaning of suffering, but the author does not like or desire only the answer that was given to Job.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Critics question whether even the main body of the book, not counting the chapters that exist only in the Latin version and in Greek fragments, has a single author.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Kalisch, De Faye, and Charles hold that no fewer than five people worked on the text.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] However, Gunkel points to the unity in character and holds that the book is written by a single author; the author of 2 Esdras has also been suggested to have written the Syriac Apocalypse of Baruch.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] In any case, the two texts may date from about the same time, and one almost certainly depends on the other.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Critics have widely debated the origin of the book.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Hidden under two layers of translation, determining whether the author was Roman, Alexandrian, or Judean is impossible.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The book is found in the Orthodox Slavonic Bible (Ostrog Bible, Elizabeth Bible, and later consequently Russian Synodal Bible).
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 2 Esdras is in the Apocrypha of the King James Version, and Pope Clement VIII placed it in an appendix to the Vulgate along with 3 Esdras and the Prayer of Manasseh "lest they perish entirely".
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The chapters corresponding to 4 Ezra, i.e.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 2 Esdras 3–14, make up the *Book of II Izra*, aka *Izra Sutuel*, canonical in the Orthodox Tewahedo churches; it was also widely cited by the early Church Fathers, particularly Ambrose, as the 'third book of Esdras'.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] It may also be found in many larger English Bibles included as part of the Biblical apocrypha, as they exist in the King James Version, the Revised Version, the Revised Standard Version, and the earliest editions of the Catholic Douay–Rheims Bible, among others.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The *introitus* of the traditional Requiem of the Extraordinary Form of the 1962 Tridentine Missal of the Catholic Church is loosely based on 2:34–35: "Eternal rest grant unto them, O Lord, and let perpetual light shine upon them." Several other liturgical prayers are taken from the book.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The same chapter, verses 36 and 37, is cited in the Introit of Pentecost Tuesday, "*Accipite jucunditatem gloriae vestrae, alleluia: gratias agentes Deo, alleluia: qui vos ad caelestia regna vocavit, alleluia, alleluia, alleluia*.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] 77 *Attendite, popule meus, legem meam: inclinate aurem vestram in verba oris mei.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Accipite*. – Receive the delight of your glory, alleluia, giving thanks to God, alleluia, Who hath called ye to the heavenly kingdoms, alleluia, alleluia, alleluia.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Psalm 77 Attend, O my people, to my law: incline your ears to the words of my mouth.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Receive.” The Alleluia verse *Crastina die* for the Vigil Mass of Christmas in the Roman Missal is taken from chapter 16, verse 52.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] Christopher Columbus quoted verse 6:42, which describes the Earth as created with six parts land and one part water, in his appeal to the Catholic Monarchs for financial support for his first voyage of exploration.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The book is appointed as a scripture reading in the Ordinariate’s Evensong service for All Hallows' Eve.
[src:extinction/2-esdras] The work is included in the New Revised Standard Version-based *The Life with God Study Bible*.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] American Christian radio host Harold Camping stated in his 2005 book *Time Has an End* that the rapture and Judgment Day would take place on May 21, 2011, and that the end of the world would take place five months later on October 21, 2011.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping, who was then president of the Family Radio Christian network, claimed the Bible as his source and said May 21 would be the date of the rapture and the day of judgment "beyond the shadow of a doubt".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping suggested that it would occur at 6 p.m. local time, with the rapture sweeping the globe time zone by time zone, while some of his supporters claimed that around 200 million people (approximately 3% of the world's population) would be 'raptured'.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping had, in the early 1990s, posited that the rapture might occur in September 1994.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The vast majority of Christian groups, including most Protestant and Catholic believers, did not accept Camping's predictions; some explicitly rejected them, citing Bible passages including the words of Jesus stating "about that day or hour no one knows" (Matthew 24:36).
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] An interview with a group of church leaders noted that all of them had scheduled church services as usual for Sunday, May 22.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Following the failure of the prediction, media attention shifted to the response from Camping and his followers.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 23, Camping stated that May 21 had been a "spiritual" day of judgment, and that the physical rapture would occur on October 21, 2011, simultaneously with the destruction of the universe by God.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] However, on October 16, Camping admitted to an interviewer that he did not know when the end would come, and made no public comment after October 21 passed without his predicted apocalypse.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In March 2012, Camping "humbly acknowledged" in a letter to Family Radio listeners that he had been mistaken, that the attempt to predict a date was "sinful", and that critics had been right in pointing to the scriptural text "of that day and hour knoweth no man".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He added that he was searching the Bible "even more fervently [...] not to find dates, but to be more faithful in our understanding".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping presented several arguments labeled "numerological" by the mainstream media, which he considered biblical proofs, in favor of the May 21 end time.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] A civil engineer by training, Camping stated he had attempted to work out mathematically based prophecies in the Bible for decades.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In an interview with the *San Francisco Chronicle* he explained "...
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] I was an engineer, I was very interested in the numbers.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In 1970, Camping dated the Great Flood to 4990 BC.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping takes the 17th day of the second month mentioned in Genesis 7:11 to be May 21, and hence predicts the rapture to occur on this date.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The number of days (as calculated below) between April 1, 33 AD, and May 21, 2011, AD, is 722,500.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] If 1,978 is multiplied by 365.2422 days (the number of days in a solar, as distinct from lunar, year), the result is 722,449.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The time between April 1 and May 21 is 51 days.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping was not precise about the timing of the event, saying that "maybe" we can know the hour.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He has suggested that "days" in the Bible refer to daylight hours particularly.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In Camping's book *1994?*, self-published in 1992, he predicted that the end times would come on September 6, 1994.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] When the rapture failed to occur on the appointed day, Camping said he had made a mathematical error.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping's rapture prediction, along with some of his other teachings and beliefs, sparked controversy in the Christian and secular Western worlds.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] His critics often quoted Bible verses (such as Matthew 24:36) they interpret as saying that the date of the end will never be known by anyone but God until it actually happens.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] However, Camping and his followers responded that this principle applied only during the "church age" or pre-Tribulation period and did not apply to the present day, citing other verses (such as 1 Thessalonians 5:1–5:5) in their rebuttal.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In a 2001 pamphlet, Camping asserted that believers should "flee the church", resigning from any church they belong to, because the "Church Age" is over and the "Great Tribulation" has begun.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] This assertion was controversial and drew "a flurry of attacks".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Yamauchi critiqued Camping's dating of the Flood when Camping first published his ideas in 1970.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Criticism of the May 21 prediction ranged from serious critique to ridicule.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Skinner, writing at the *Huffington Post*, noted the "long history of failed speculation" about the end times and cautioned that end-of-the-world talk can lead Christians to social passivity instead of "working for the world's redemption".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Some columnists mocked the prediction with humorous essays.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In 2010, Marie Exley of Colorado Springs made news by purchasing advertising space in her locality, promoting the alleged rapture date on a number of park benches.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] After that, more than 5000 "Judgment Day" billboards were erected in locations across the world, including the Dominican Republic, Ethiopia, Ghana, Indonesia, Israel, Jamaica, Jordan, Lebanon, Lesotho, the Philippines, Tanzania and the United States.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Some people adorned their vehicles with the information.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Many who believed in the prediction took time off work to prepare for the Rapture.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Others spent their life savings on advertising material to publicize the prophecy.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] One retired transportation agency worker from New York spent $140,000 on advertising.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio spent over US$100 million on the information campaign, financed by sales and swap of broadcast outlets.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] According to former Family Radio employee Matt Tuter, "We had a pool of about $100 million dollars, and [Camping] spent it like no tomorrow." On October 27, 2010, they launched "Project Caravan".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Five recreational vehicles announcing on their sides that Judgment Day was to begin on May 21, 2011, were sent out from their headquarters in Oakland, California, to Seattle, Washington.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Upon arrival, teams were sent out to distribute tracts.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The caravan subsequently made stops in many states in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping's prediction and his promotion of it via his radio network and other promotional means spread the prediction globally.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Some followers of Camping gave up their jobs, sold their homes, stopped investing in their children's college funds and spent large sums promoting Camping's claims.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] About 5,000 ethnic Hmong gathered at a remote town in Vietnam's Mường Nhé District in Điện Biên Province in early May, where they planned to await the arrival of Christ.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The Vietnamese government broke up the gathering and arrested some people, describing them as "extremists".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Pastor Doan Trung Tin indicated that a translated version of Camping's prediction had influenced about 300 of his parishioners to go to the assembly point, selling their belongings to be able to afford the journey via bus.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Many of the Hmong Christians who escaped arrest were reportedly forced into hiding after the gathering.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 19, 2011, the search term "end of the world may 21st" reached second position on Google Trends, based on the popularity of the search term in the United States.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The related searches "Harold Camping", "May 21 doomsday", and "May 21 rapture" were also represented among the top 10 positions.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The New York Police Department stated: "We don't plan any additional coverage for the end of the world.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On the weekend of May 21–22, the Family Radio headquarters was closed with a note stating, "This office is closed.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Sorry we missed you!" The Family Radio network remained on the air during May 21 and May 22, mostly broadcasting its normal schedule of programming, but with no mention of the rapture and without the usual replays of Harold Camping's program *Open Forum*.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On Sunday, May 22, Camping emerged briefly from his home, saying "Give me a day, no interviews today ...
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] I've got to live with it, I've got to think it out." He said he would make a public statement on Monday, May 23.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping said he was "flabbergasted" that the rapture did not occur, that he was "looking for answers", and would say more when he returned to work on May 23.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 23, he returned to his *Open Forum* radio program, with members of the press in attendance, and, departing from his typical format, took questions from the reporters present instead of from callers.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He stated that May 21 had been an "invisible judgment day" which was purely spiritual in nature, and that he now realized that the physical rapture would take place on October 21, simultaneously with the destruction of the universe.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] "We've always said May 21 was the day, but we didn't understand altogether the spiritual meaning," he said.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He said that the publicity campaign would not continue, explaining that since God's judgment had already occurred, there was no point in continuing to warn people about it.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He added, "We're not going to put up any more billboards – in fact they're coming down right now." Responding to a question, Camping said his organization would not return money donated by followers to publicize the May 21 prediction, saying "We're not at the end.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] A Family Radio staffer suggested that the delay might be God's way of separating true believers from those willing to doubt the "clear biblical warnings".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Individual followers who had spent time and money promoting Camping's prediction were "crestfallen" after May 21 passed without evidence of the rapture.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] A New York man commented "I was doing what I've been instructed to do through the Bible, but now I've been stymied.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] There were rumors that people had killed themselves or attempted suicide to escape the predicted Judgment Day.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] There was one documented case, in which a 14-year-old Russian girl killed herself on May 21.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Her family told a Russian tabloid, *LifeNews*, that she did it because of her fear of the "terrible sufferings" predicted by Camping.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] A group from the Calvary Bible Church in Milpitas, California offered a session to comfort those who had believed in the prophecy.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Church deacon James Bynum told a local newspaper that "We are here because we care about these people.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In response to the prediction, more than 830,000 registered as attending a "Post Rapture Looting" event on Facebook.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The group American Atheists sponsored billboards in several American cities declaring the rapture to be "nonsense".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The group Seattle Atheists formed the Rapture Relief Fund which they said would be used "to help survivors of any Armageddon-sized disaster in the Puget Sound area"; since the rapture failed to occur on May 21, the money will fund a camp that teaches children about science and critical thinking.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The comic strip *Doonesbury* spent the week leading up to the predicted day making fun of the prediction.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On May 21, groups of protesters gathered at Family Radio's headquarters in Oakland to mock the evangelical broadcaster's failed prediction.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] One group released human-shaped helium balloons to simulate souls rising to heaven, while another person played The Doors' song "The End" over a boombox.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Many atheist and secular groups in the United States hosted "Rapture parties" on May 21.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] American Atheists hosted a two-day conference over the May 21 weekend in Oakland, not far from Camping's radio station.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] President David Silverman commented, "We're going to poke fun at these people, but in the end we need to keep in mind that there are people being hurt here ...
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] We're hoping people look at this and learn to use their brains ... so we don't have an occurrence of this in 2012" (when some believed the Maya predicted as the Earth's final destruction).
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Nickel Creek's album *A Dotted Line* features a song entitled "21st of May" that is based on the prediction.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping continued to predict that October 21 would mark the end of the world, based on adding the 153 fish of John 21:11 to May 21, but modified his prediction with words like *probably* and *maybe*.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] "I really am beginning to think as I've restudied these matters that there's going to be no big display of any kind," Camping said in a podcast.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] No statement was issued by Camping or Family Radio on October 21 or 22.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] It was later reported that Camping told an interviewer on October 16 that God has not given anyone the power to know exactly when the rapture would come.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He retired from his leadership position at Family Radio.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Sometime after October 21, Family Radio posted an audio message from Harold Camping on their home page.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In the message, Camping stated, regarding end times prophecy, that "we are finding it very very difficult".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He also told followers to "not feel abandoned by God" and that "God is still in charge of everything".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] As October 21 approached, the Freedom from Religion Foundation bought space on more than 40 billboards in the Bay Area to mock Camping's predictions and urge viewers to use rational judgment.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The billboards featured slogans such as, "Fool me once...", "Still here", and "Every day is judgment day.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Media reports on October 21 and 22 stressed that Camping had been "wrong again".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The *International Business Times* proclaimed him a "false prophet".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On October 21, 2011, *Time* magazine's website listed Camping's end times predictions as one of the "Top 10 Failed Predictions", a list compiled in Camping's "honor".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio removed from its web site the archive of audio recordings of Camping's Open Forum program recorded prior to May 2011.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] On June 9, 2011, Camping suffered a stroke and was hospitalized.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Family Radio broadcast reruns of his May 23 – June 9 *Open Forum* segments for several weeks.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] As of June 23, Family Radio began to provide new programming in his time slot.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In April 2012, Family Radio sold its Philadelphia station WKDN to Merlin Media; upon its formal takeover of the station, WKDN broadcast the R.E.M. song "It's the End of the World as We Know It (And I Feel Fine)" for several hours as a stunt referencing the failed prediction.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Camping died on December 15, 2013, at the age of 92, as a result of complications from a fall at home two weeks earlier.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] His death was confirmed by an employee of the network.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] In September 2018, Family Radio announced it would no longer air programs featuring the voice of Harold Camping, and would no longer distribute literature of Camping's teachings.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The decision was made as part of an effort to both move away from Camping's theology, and to reintroduce programs from outside ministries into the network's schedule.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] The changes went into effect on October 8, 2018.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] McCann continued to teach that October 21, 2011, would be the end of the world, even after the failed May 21, 2011 prediction.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] And after October 21, 2011, he taught that the end of the world would occur in March 2012.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] At the end of 2012, McCann began teaching the possibility that the last day would be October 7, 2015.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He said that there was "a strong likelihood that this will happen" and "an unlikely possibility that it will not".
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] According to his interpretation of 2 Peter 3, the world will be destroyed by fire.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Later, McCann said it was "surprising" that the world did not end at the predicted date.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] This date was arrived at by adding 1,600 days (taken from Revelation 14:20) to May 21, 2011, which McCann continued to teach at least well into 2012 was the beginning of the day of judgment.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] He noted that October 7, 2015, is the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles, and exactly 10,000 days from May 21, 1988, which he claims is the date the Church Age came to an end.
[src:extinction/2011-end-times-prediction] Robert Fitzpatrick wrote a book entitled *The Doomsday Code*, based on the writings of Camping.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The **2012 phenomenon** was a range of eschatological beliefs that cataclysmic or transformative events would occur on or around 21 December 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Various astronomical alignments and numerological formulae were proposed for this date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A New Age interpretation held that the date marked the start of a period during which Earth and its inhabitants would undergo a positive physical or spiritual transformation, and that 21 December 2012 would mark the beginning of a new era.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Others suggested that the date marked the end of the world or a similar catastrophe.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Scholars from various disciplines quickly dismissed predictions of cataclysmic events as they arose.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Mayan scholars stated that no classic Mayan accounts forecast impending doom, and the idea that the Long Count calendar ends in 2012 misrepresented Mayan history and culture.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers rejected the various proposed doomsday scenarios as pseudoscience, having been refuted by elementary astronomical observations.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] December 2012 marked the conclusion of a *bʼakʼtun*—a time period in the Mesoamerican Long Count calendar, used in Mesoamerica prior to the arrival of Europeans.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Although the Long Count was most likely invented by the Olmec, it has become closely associated with the Maya civilization, whose classic period lasted from 250 to 900 AD.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The writing system of the classic Maya has been substantially deciphered, meaning that a text corpus of their written and inscribed material has survived from before the Spanish conquest of Yucatán.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Thus, the Maya date of 8.3.2.10.15 represents 8 bʼakʼtuns, 3 kʼatuns, 2 tuns, 10 uinals and 15 days.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There is a strong tradition of "world ages" in Maya literature, but the record has been distorted, leaving several possibilities open to interpretation.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] According to the *Popol Vuh*, a compilation of the creation accounts of the Kʼicheʼ Maya of the Colonial-era highlands, the current world is the fourth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The *Popol Vuh* describes the gods first creating three failed worlds, followed by a successful fourth world in which humanity was placed.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the Maya Long Count, the previous world ended after 13 bʼakʼtuns, or roughly 5,125 years.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Long Count's "zero date" was set at a point in the past marking the end of the third world and the beginning of the current one, which corresponds to 11 August 3114 BC in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This means that the fourth world reached the end of its 13th bʼakʼtun, or Maya date 13.0.0.0.0, on 21 December 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 1957, Mayanist and astronomer Maud Worcester Makemson wrote that "the completion of a Great Period of 13 bʼakʼtuns would have been of the utmost significance to the Maya." In 1966, Michael D.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Coe wrote in *The Maya* that "there is a suggestion ... that Armageddon would overtake the degenerate peoples of the world and all creation on the final day of the 13th [bʼakʼtun].
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Coe's interpretation was repeated by other scholars through the early 1990s.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In contrast, later researchers said that, while the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun would perhaps be a cause for celebration, it did not mark the end of the calendar.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "There is nothing in the Maya or Aztec or ancient Mesoamerican prophecy to suggest that they prophesied a sudden or major change of any sort in 2012," said Mayanist scholar Mark Van Stone.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "The notion of a 'Great Cycle' coming to an end is completely a modern invention." In 1990, Mayanist scholars Linda Schele and David Freidel argued that the Maya "did not conceive this to be the end of creation, as many have suggested".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Susan Milbrath, curator of Latin American Art and Archaeology at the Florida Museum of Natural History, stated that, "We have no record or knowledge that [the Maya] would think the world would come to an end" in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Wyllys Andrews V, director of the Tulane University Middle American Research Institute.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Maya were looking for a guarantee that nothing would change.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Several prominent individuals representing Maya of Guatemala decried the suggestion that the world would end with the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Ricardo Cajas, president of the *Colectivo de Organizaciones Indígenas de Guatemala*, said the date did not represent an end of humanity but that the new cycle "supposes changes in human consciousness".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Martín Sacalxot, of the office of Guatemala's Human Rights Ombudsman (*Procurador de los Derechos Humanos*), said that the end of the calendar has nothing to do with the end of the world or the year 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The European association of the Maya with eschatology dates back to the time of Christopher Columbus, who was compiling a work called *Libro de las profecías* during the voyage in 1502 when he first heard about the "Maia" on Guanaja, an island off the north coast of Honduras.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Influenced by the writings of Bishop Pierre d'Ailly, Columbus believed that his discovery of "most distant" lands (and, by extension, the Maya themselves) was prophesied and would bring about the Apocalypse.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] End-times fears were widespread during the early years of the Spanish Conquest as the result of popular astrological predictions in Europe of a second Great Flood for the year 1524.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the 1900s, German scholar Ernst Förstemann interpreted the last page of the Dresden Codex as a representation of the end of the world in a cataclysmic flood.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He made reference to the destruction of the world and an apocalypse, though he made no reference to the 13th bʼakʼtun or 2012 and it was not clear that he was referring to a future event.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] His ideas were repeated by archaeologist Sylvanus Morley, who directly paraphrased Förstemann and added his own embellishments, writing, "Finally, on the last page of the manuscript, is depicted the Destruction of the World ...
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Here, indeed, is portrayed with a graphic touch the final all-engulfing cataclysm" in the form of a great flood.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] These comments were later repeated in Morley's book, *The Ancient Maya*, the first edition of which was published in 1946.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] It is not certain what significance the classic Maya gave to the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Most classic Maya inscriptions are strictly historical and do not make any prophetic declarations.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Two items in the Maya classical corpus do mention the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun: Tortuguero Monument 6 and La Corona Hieroglyphic Stairway 12.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Tortuguero site, which lies in southernmost Tabasco, Mexico, dates from the 7th century AD and consists of a series of inscriptions mostly in honor of the contemporary ruler Bahlam Ahau.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] One inscription, known as Tortuguero Monument 6, is the only inscription known to refer to bʼakʼtun 13 in any detail.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Very little is known about the god Bʼolon Yokteʼ.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] According to an article by Mayanists Markus Eberl and Christian Prager in *British Anthropological Reports*, his name is composed of the elements "nine", ʼOK-teʼ (the meaning of which is unknown), and "god".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Confusion in classical period inscriptions suggests that the name was already ancient and unfamiliar to contemporary scribes.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He also appears in inscriptions from Palenque, Usumacinta, and La Mar as a god of war, conflict, and the underworld.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In one stele he is portrayed with a rope tied around his neck, and in another with an incense bag, together signifying a sacrifice to end a cycle of years.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Based on observations of modern Maya rituals, Gronemeyer and MacLeod claim that the stela refers to a celebration in which a person portraying Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh was wrapped in ceremonial garments and paraded around the site.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] They note that the association of Bolon Yokteʼ Kʼuh with bʼakʼtun 13 appears to be so important on this inscription that it supersedes more typical celebrations such as "erection of stelae, scattering of incense" and so forth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, they assert that this event was indeed planned for 2012 and not the 7th century.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Mayanist scholar Stephen Houston contests this view by arguing that future dates on Maya inscriptions were simply meant to draw parallels with contemporary events, and that the words on the stela describe a contemporary rather than a future scene.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In April–May 2012, a team of archaeologists unearthed a previously unknown inscription on a stairway at the La Corona site in Guatemala.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The inscription, on what is known as Hieroglyphic Stairway 12, describes the establishment of a royal court in Calakmul in 635 AD, and compares the then-recent completion of 13 kʼatuns with the future completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] It contains no speculation or prophecy as to what the scribes believed would happen at that time.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Maya inscriptions occasionally mention predicted future events or commemorations that would occur on dates far beyond the completion of the 13th bʼakʼtun.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Most of these are in the form of "distance dates"; Long Count dates together with an additional number, known as a Distance Number, which when added to them makes a future date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On the west panel at the Temple of Inscriptions in Palenque, a section of text projects forward to the 80th 52-year Calendar Round from the coronation of the ruler Kʼinich Janaabʼ Pakal.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Pakal's accession occurred on 9.9.2.4.8, equivalent to 27 July 615 AD in the proleptic Gregorian calendar.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The inscription begins with Pakal's birthdate of 9.8.9.13.0 (24 March, 603 AD Gregorian) and then adds the Distance Number 10.11.10.5.8 to it, arriving at a date of 21 October 4772 AD, more than 4,000 years after Pakal's time.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] According to Linda Schele, these 13s represent "the starting point of a huge odometer of time", with each acting as a zero and resetting to 1 as the numbers increase.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Thus this inscription anticipates the current universe lasting at least 2021×13×360 days, or roughly 2.687×1028 years; a time span equal to 2 quintillion times the age of the universe as determined by cosmologists.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Others have suggested that this date marks creation as having occurred after that time span.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, researchers announced the discovery of a series of Maya astronomical tables in Xultún, Guatemala which plot the movements of the Moon and other astronomical bodies over the course of 17 bʼakʼtuns.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Many assertions about the year 2012 form part of Mayanism, a non-codified collection of New Age beliefs about ancient Maya wisdom and spirituality.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The term is distinct from "Mayanist," used to refer to an academic scholar of the Maya.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Archaeoastronomer Anthony Aveni says that while the idea of "balancing the cosmos" was prominent in ancient Maya literature, the 2012 phenomenon did not draw from those traditions.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Instead, it was bound up with American concepts such as the New Age movement, 2012 millenarianism, and the belief in secret knowledge from distant times and places.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Themes found in 2012 literature included "suspicion towards mainstream Western culture", the idea of spiritual evolution, and the possibility of leading the world into the New Age by individual example or by a group's joined consciousness.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The general intent of this literature was not to warn of impending doom but "to foster counter-cultural sympathies and eventually socio-political and 'spiritual' activism".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 1975, the ending of bʼakʼtun 13 became the subject of speculation by several New Age authors, who asserted it would correspond with a global "transformation of consciousness".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some research suggests that both Argüelles and McKenna were heavily influenced in this regard by the Mayanism of American author William S.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Burroughs, who first portrayed the end of the Mayan Long Count as an apocalyptic shift of human consciousness in 1960's *The Exterminator*.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 1983, with the publication of Robert J.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Sharer's revised table of date correlations in the 4th edition of Morley's *The Ancient Maya,* each became convinced that 21 December 2012 had significant meaning.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] By 1987, the year in which he organized the Harmonic Convergence event, Argüelles was using the date 21 December 2012 in *The Mayan Factor: Path Beyond Technology*.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the Maya aligned their calendar to correspond to this phenomenon.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Anthony Aveni has dismissed all of these ideas.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2001, Robert Bast wrote the first online articles regarding the possibility of a doomsday in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2006, author Daniel Pinchbeck popularized New Age concepts about this date in his book *2012: The Return of Quetzalcoatl*, linking bʼakʼtun 13 to beliefs in crop circles, alien abduction, and personal revelations based on the use of hallucinogenic drugs and mediumship.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Pinchbeck claims to discern a "growing realization that materialism and the rational, empirical worldview that comes with it has reached its expiration date ... [w]e're on the verge of transitioning to a dispensation of consciousness that's more intuitive, mystical and shamanic".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There is no significant astronomical event tied to the Long Count's start date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Its supposed end date was tied to astronomical phenomena by esoteric, fringe, and New Age literature that placed great significance on astrology, especially astrological interpretations associated with the phenomenon of axial precession.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Chief among these ideas is the astrological concept of a "galactic alignment".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the Solar System, the planets and the Sun lie roughly within the same flat plane, known as the plane of the ecliptic.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] From our perspective on Earth, the ecliptic is the path taken by the Sun across the sky over the course of the year.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The twelve constellations that line the ecliptic are known as the zodiacal constellations, and, annually, the Sun passes through all of them in turn.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Additionally, over time, the Sun's annual cycle appears to recede very slowly backward by one degree every 72 years, or by one constellation approximately every 2,160 years.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This backward movement, called "precession", is due to a slight wobble in the Earth's axis as it spins, and can be compared to the way a spinning top wobbles as it slows down.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Over the course of 25,800 years, a period often called a Great Year, the Sun's path completes a full, 360-degree backward rotation through the zodiac.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Western astrological traditions, precession is measured from the March equinox, one of the two annual points at which the Sun is exactly halfway between its lowest and highest points in the sky.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] At the end of the 20th century and beginning of the 21st, the Sun's March equinox position was in the constellation Pisces moving back into Aquarius.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This signaled the end of one astrological age (the Age of Pisces) and the beginning of another (the Age of Aquarius).
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the Sun's December solstice position (in the northern hemisphere, the lowest point on its annual path; in the southern hemisphere, the highest) was in the constellation of Sagittarius, one of two constellations in which the zodiac intersects with the Milky Way.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Every year, on the December solstice, the Sun and the Milky Way, appear (from the surface of the Earth) to come into alignment, and every year precession caused a slight shift in the Sun's position in the Milky Way.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Given that the Milky Way is between 10° and 20° wide, it takes between 700 and 1,400 years for the Sun's December solstice position to precess through it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2012 it was about halfway through the Milky Way, crossing the galactic equator.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the Sun's December solstice fell on 21 December.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Mystical speculations about the precession of the equinoxes and the Sun's proximity to the center of the Milky Way appeared in *Hamlet's Mill* (1969) by Giorgio de Santillana and Hertha von Deschend.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] These were quoted and expanded upon by Terence and Dennis McKenna in *The Invisible Landscape* (1975).
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Adherents to the idea, following a theory first proposed by Munro Edmonson, alleged that the Maya based their calendar on observations of the Great Rift or Dark Rift, a band of dark dust clouds in the Milky Way, which, according to some scholars, the Maya called the *Xibalba be* or "Black Road".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins claims that the Maya were aware of where the ecliptic intersected the Black Road and gave this position in the sky a special significance in their cosmology.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins said that precession would align the Sun precisely with the galactic equator at the 2012 winter solstice.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed that the classical Maya anticipated this conjunction and celebrated it as the harbinger of a profound spiritual transition for mankind.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] New Age proponents of the galactic alignment hypothesis argued that, just as astrology uses the positions of stars and planets to make claims of future events, the Maya plotted their calendars with the objective of preparing for significant world events.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins attributed the insights of ancient Maya shamans about the Galactic Center to their use of psilocybin mushrooms, psychoactive toads, and other psychedelics.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins also associated the *Xibalba be* with a "world tree", drawing on studies of contemporary (not ancient) Maya cosmology.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers such as David Morrison argue that the galactic equator is an entirely arbitrary line and can never be precisely drawn, because it is impossible to determine the Milky Way's exact boundaries, which vary depending on clarity of view.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins claimed he drew his conclusions about the location of the galactic equator from observations taken at above 11,000 feet (3,400 m), an altitude that gives a clearer image of the Milky Way than the Maya had access to.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Furthermore, since the Sun is half a degree wide, its solstice position takes 36 years to precess its full width.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jenkins himself noted that even given his determined location for the line of the galactic equator, its most precise convergence with the center of the Sun already occurred in 1998, and so asserts that, rather than 2012, the galactic alignment instead focuses on a multi-year period centered in 1998.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There is no clear evidence that the classic Maya were aware of precession.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some Maya scholars, such as Barbara MacLeod, Michael Grofe, Eva Hunt, Gordon Brotherston, and Anthony Aveni, have suggested that some Mayan holy dates were timed to precessional cycles, but scholarly opinion on the subject remains divided.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There is also little evidence, archaeological or historical, that the Maya placed any importance on solstices or equinoxes.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] It is possible that only the earliest among Mesoamericans observed solstices, but this is also a disputed issue among Mayanists.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There is also no evidence that the classic Maya attached any importance to the Milky Way; there is no glyph in their writing system to represent it, and no astronomical or chronological table tied to it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "Timewave zero" is a numerological formula that purports to calculate the ebb and flow of "novelty", defined as increase over time in the universe's interconnectedness, or organized complexity.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Terence McKenna claimed that the universe has a teleological attractor at the end of time that increases interconnectedness.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He believed this which would eventually reach a singularity of infinite complexity in 2012, at which point anything and everything imaginable would occur simultaneously.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He conceived this idea over several years in the early to mid-1970s whilst using psilocybin mushrooms and DMT.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The scientific community considers novelty theory to be pseudoscience.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] McKenna expressed "novelty" in a computer program which produces a waveform known as "timewave zero" or the "timewave".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Based on McKenna's interpretation of the King Wen sequence of the *I Ching*, an ancient Chinese book on divination, the graph purports to show great periods of novelty corresponding with major shifts in humanity's biological and sociocultural evolution.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] He believed that the events of any given time are resonantly related to the events of other times, and chose the atomic bombing of Hiroshima as the basis for calculating his end date of November 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] When he later discovered this date's proximity to the end of the 13th bʼakʼtun of the Maya calendar, he revised his hypothesis so that the two dates matched.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The 1975 first edition of *The Invisible Landscape* referred to 2012 (but no specific day during the year) only twice.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the 1993 second edition, McKenna employed Sharer's date of 21 December 2012 throughout.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The idea that the year 2012 presaged a world cataclysm, the end of the world, or the end of human civilization, became a subject of popular media speculation as the date of 21 December 2012 approached.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This idea was promulgated by many pages on the Internet, particularly on YouTube.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel was criticized for its "quasi-documentaries" about the subject that "sacrifice[d] accuracy for entertainment".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some people interpreted the galactic alignment apocalyptically, claiming that its occurrence would somehow create a combined gravitational effect between the Sun and the supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy (known as Sagittarius A*), creating havoc on Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Apart from the "galactic alignment" already having happened in 1998, the Sun's apparent path through the zodiac as seen from Earth did not take it near the true galactic center, but rather several degrees above it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Even were this not the case, Sagittarius A* is 30,000 light years from Earth; it would have to have been more than 6 million times closer to cause any gravitational disruption to Earth's Solar System.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This reading of the alignment was included on the History Channel documentary *Decoding the Past*.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] John Major Jenkins complained that a science fiction writer co-authored the documentary, and he went on to characterize it as "45 minutes of unabashed doomsday hype and the worst kind of inane sensationalism".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday used the term "galactic alignment" to describe a different phenomenon proposed by some scientists to explain a pattern in mass extinctions supposedly observed in the fossil record.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] According to the Shiva hypothesis, mass extinctions are not random, but recur every 26 million years.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] To account for this, it was suggested that vertical oscillations made by the Sun on its 250-million-year orbit of the galactic center cause it to regularly pass through the galactic plane.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] When the Sun's orbit takes it outside the galactic plane which bisects the galactic disc, the influence of the galactic tide is weaker.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This "alignment" takes place over tens of millions of years, and could never be timed to an exact date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Evidence shows that the Sun passed through the plane bisecting the galactic disc three million years ago and in 2012 was moving farther above it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A third suggested alignment was some sort of planetary conjunction occurring on 21 December 2012; there was no conjunction on that date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Multi-planet alignments did occur in both 2000 and 2010, each with no ill result for the Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jupiter is the largest planet in the Solar System, being larger than all other planets combined.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] When Jupiter is near opposition, the difference in gravitational force that the Earth experiences is less than 1% of the force that the Earth feels daily from the Moon.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Another idea tied to 2012 involved a geomagnetic reversal (often referred to as a pole shift by proponents), possibly triggered by a massive solar flare, that would release an energy equal to 100 billion atomic bombs.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This belief was supposedly supported by observations that the Earth's magnetic field was weakening, which could precede a reversal of the north and south magnetic poles, and the arrival of the next solar maximum, which was expected sometime around 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Most scientific estimates say that geomagnetic reversals take between 1,000 and 10,000 years to complete, and do not start on any particular date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration predicted that the solar maximum would peak in late 2013 or 2014, and that it would be fairly weak, with a below-average number of sunspots.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] There was no scientific evidence linking a solar maximum to a geomagnetic reversal, which is driven by forces entirely within the Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A solar maximum does affect satellite and cellular phone communications.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 23 July 2012, a massive, potentially damaging, solar storm came within nine days of striking Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some believers in a 2012 doomsday claimed that a planet called Planet X, or Nibiru, would collide with or pass by the Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This idea, which had appeared in various forms since 1995, initially predicted Doomsday in May 2003, but proponents abandoned that date after it passed without incident.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The idea originated from claims of channeling alien beings and is widely ridiculed.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Astronomers calculated that such an object so close to Earth would be visible to anyone looking up at the night sky.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Author Graham Hancock, in his book *Fingerprints of the Gods*, interpreted Coe's remarks in *Breaking the Maya Code* as evidence for the prophecy of a global cataclysm.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Filmmaker Roland Emmerich later credited the book with inspiring his 2009 disaster film *2012*.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Other speculations regarding doomsday in 2012 included predictions by the Web Bot project, a computer program that purports to predict the future by analyzing Internet chatter.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Commentators have rejected claims that the bot is able to predict natural disasters, as opposed to human-caused disasters like stock market crashes.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 date was also loosely tied to the long-running concept of the **photon belt**, which predicted a form of interaction between Earth and Alcyone, the largest star of the Pleiades cluster.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Critics argued that photons cannot form belts, that the Pleiades, located more than 400 light years away, could have no effect on Earth, and that the Solar System, rather than getting closer to the Pleiades, was in fact moving farther away from it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Some media outlets tied the fact that the red supergiant star Betelgeuse would undergo a supernova at some point in the future to the 2012 phenomenon.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] While Betelgeuse was certainly in the final stages of its life, and would die as a supernova, there was no way to predict the timing of the event to within 100,000 years.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] To be a threat to Earth, a supernova would need to be no further than 25 light years from the Solar System.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Betelgeuse is roughly 600 light years away, and so its supernova would not affect Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In December 2011, NASA's Francis Reddy issued a press release debunking the possibility of a supernova occurring in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In December 2010, an article, first published in examiner.com and later referenced in the English-language edition of *Pravda* claimed, citing a Second Digitized Sky Survey photograph as evidence, that SETI had detected three large spacecraft due to arrive at Earth in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Astronomer and debunker Phil Plait noted that by using the small-angle formula, one could determine that if the object in the photo were as large as claimed, it would have had to be closer to Earth than the Moon, which would mean it would already have arrived.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In January 2011, Seth Shostak, chief astronomer of SETI, issued a press release debunking the claims.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon spread widely after coming to public notice, particularly on the Internet, and hundreds of thousands of websites made reference to it.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "Ask an Astrobiologist", a NASA public outreach website, received over 5,000 questions from the public on the subject from 2007, some asking whether they should kill themselves, their children or their pets.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] At least one suicide was directly linked to fear of a 2012 apocalypse, with others anecdotally reported.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jared Lee Loughner, the perpetrator of the 2011 Tucson shooting, followed 2012-related predictions.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A panel of scientists questioned on the topic at a plenary session at the Astronomical Society of the Pacific contended that the Internet played a substantial role in allowing this doomsday date to gain more traction than previous similar panics.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Beginning in 2000, the small French village of Bugarach, population 189, began receiving visits from "esoterics"—mystic believers who had concluded that the local mountain, Pic de Bugarach, was the ideal location to weather the transformative events of 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2011, the local mayor, Jean-Pierre Delord, began voicing fears to the international press that the small town would be overwhelmed by an influx of thousands of visitors in 2012, even suggesting he might call in the army.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "We've seen a huge rise in visitors", Delord told *The Independent* in March 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] "Already this year more than 20,000 people have climbed right to the top, and last year we had 10,000 hikers, which was a significant rise on the previous 12 months.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] They think Pic de Bugarach is 'un garage à ovnis' [a garage for UFOs].
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The villagers are exasperated: the exaggerated importance of something which they see as completely removed from reality is bewildering.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] After 21 December, this will surely return to normal." In December 2012, the French government placed 100 police and firefighters around both Bugarach and Pic de Bugarach, limiting access to potential visitors.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Ultimately, only about 1,000 visitors appeared at the height of the "event".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Two raves were foiled, 12 people had to be turned away from the peak, and 5 people were arrested for carrying weapons.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jean-Pierre Delord was criticised by members of the community for failing to take advantage of the media attention and promote the region.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Turkish village of Şirince, near Ephesus, expected to receive over 60,000 visitors on 21 December 2012, as New Age mystics believed its "positive energy" would aid in weathering the catastrophe.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Only a fraction of that number actually arrived, with a substantial component being police and journalists, and the expected windfall failed to materialise.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Similarly, the pyramid-like mountain of Rtanj, in the Serbian Carpathians, attracted attention, due to rumors that it would emit a powerful force shield on the day, protecting those in the vicinity.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Russia, inmates of a women's prison experienced "a collective mass psychosis" in the weeks leading up to the supposed doomsday, while residents of a factory town near Moscow reportedly emptied a supermarket of matches, candles, food and other supplies.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Minister of Emergency Situations declared in response that according to "methods of monitoring what is occurring on the planet Earth", there would be no apocalypse in December.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In December 2012, Vatican astronomer Rev.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] José Funes wrote in the Vatican newspaper *L'Osservatore Romano* that apocalyptic theories around 2012 were "not even worth discussing".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In May 2011, 5,000-7,000 Hmong ethnic people in Dien Bien province, Vietnam held a protest on the grounds that the end of the world was coming, and the Hmong people would be evacuated to their own Hmong country by "supernatural force".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Vietnamese media and government believe that this is a trick of the Hmong ethnic separatist forces.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In China, up to a thousand members of the Christian cult Almighty God were arrested after claiming that the end of bʼakʼtun 13 marked the end of the world, and that it was time to overthrow Communism.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Shoppers were reported to be hoarding supplies of candles in anticipation of coming darkness, while online retailer Taobao sold tickets to board Noah's Ark to customers.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Bookings for wedding ceremonies on 21 December 2012 were saturated in several cities.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 14 December 2012, a man in Henan province attacked and wounded twenty-three children with a knife.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Authorities suspected the man had been "influenced" by the prediction of the upcoming apocalypse.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Academics in China attributed the widespread belief in the 2012 doomsday in their country to a lack of scientific literacy and a mistrust of the government-controlled media.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 6 December 2012, Australian Prime Minister Julia Gillard delivered a hoax speech for the radio station triple J in which she declared "My dear remaining fellow Australians; the end of the world is coming.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Jasper Tsang, president of Hong Kong's Legislative Council, adjourned the legislature's sitting on 20 December 2012 by announcing that he "would not permit the world to end" as the legislature had to meet again in January 2013, to the laughter of MPs.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Mesoamerican countries that once formed part of the Maya civilization—Mexico, Belize, Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador—all organized festivities to commemorate the end of bʼakʼtun 13 at the largest Maya sites.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2011, the Maya town of Tapachula in Chiapas activated an eight-foot digital clock counting down the days until the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, major events took place at Chichén Itzá in Mexico and Tikal in Guatemala.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In El Salvador, the largest event was held at Tazumal, and in Honduras, at Copán.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In all of these archaeological sites, Maya rituals were held at dawn led by shamans and Maya priests.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On the final day of bʼakʼtun 13, residents of Yucatán and other regions formerly dominated by the ancient Maya celebrated what they saw as the dawn of a new, better era.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] According to official figures from Mexico's National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH), about 50,000 people visited Mexican archaeological sites on 21 December 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Of those, 10,000 visited Chichén Itzá in Yucatán, 9,900 visited Tulum in Quintana Roo, and 8,000 visited Palenque in Chiapas.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] An additional 10,000 people visited Teotihuacan near Mexico City, which is not a Maya site.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The main ceremony in Chichén Itzá was held at dawn in the plaza of the Temple of Kukulkán, one of the principal symbols of Maya culture.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The archaeological site was opened two hours early to receive thousands of tourists, mostly foreigners who came to participate in events scheduled for the end of bʼakʼtun 13.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The fire ceremony at Tikal was held at dawn in the main plaza of the Temple of the Great Jaguar.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The ceremony was led by Guatemalan and foreign priests.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The President of Guatemala, Otto Pérez, and of Costa Rica, Laura Chinchilla, participated in the event as special guests.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] During the ceremony the priests asked for unity, peace and the end of discrimination and racism, with the hope that the start of a new cycle will be a "new dawn".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] About 3,000 people participated in the event.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Most of these events were organized by agencies of the Mexican and Central American governments, and their respective tourism industries expected to attract thousands of visitors.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Mexico is visited by about 22 million foreigners in a typical year.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the national tourism agency expected to attract 52 million visitors just to the regions of Chiapas, Yucatán, Quintana Roo, Tabasco and Campeche.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A Maya activist group in Guatemala, Oxlaljuj Ajpop, objected to the commercialization of the date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A spokesman from the Conference of Maya Ministers commented that for them the Tikal ceremony is not a show for tourists but something spiritual and personal.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The secretary of the Great Council of Ancestral Authorities commented that living Maya felt they were excluded from the activities in Tikal.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] This group held a parallel ceremony, and complained that the date has been used for commercial gain.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In addition, before the main Tikal ceremony, about 200 Maya protested the celebration because they felt excluded.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Most modern Maya were indifferent to the ceremonies, and the small number of people still practising ancient rites held solemn, more private ceremonies.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Osvaldo Gomez, a technical advisor to the Tikal site, complained that many visitors during the celebration had illegally climbed the stairs of the Temple of the Masks, causing "irreparable" damage.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Brazil, Décio Colla, the Mayor of the City of São Francisco de Paula, Rio Grande do Sul, mobilized the population to prepare for the end of the world by stocking up on food and supplies.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the city of Corguinho, in the Mato Grosso do Sul, a colony was built for survivors of the expected tragedy.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Alto Paraíso de Goiás, the hotels also made specific reservations for prophetic dates.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Bolivia, President Evo Morales participated in Quechua and Aymara rituals, organized with government support, to commemorate the Southern solstice that took place in Isla del Sol, in the southern part of Lake Titicaca.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] During the event, Morales proclaimed the beginning of "*Pachakuti*", meaning the world's wake up to a culture of life and the beginning of the end to world capitalism, and he proposed to dismantle the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 21 December 2012, the Uritorco mountain in Córdoba, Argentina was closed, as a mass suicide there had been proposed on Facebook.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the United States, sales of private underground blast shelters increased noticeably after 2009, with many construction companies' advertisements calling attention to the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In Michigan, schools were closed for the Christmas holidays two days early, in part because rumours of the 2012 apocalypse were raising fears of repeat shootings similar to that at Sandy Hook.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] American reality TV stars Heidi Montag and Spencer Pratt revealed that they had spent most of their $10 million of accumulated earnings by 2010 because they believed the world would end in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The 2012 phenomenon was discussed or referenced by several media outlets.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Several TV documentaries, as well as some contemporary fictional references to the year 2012, referred to 21 December as the day of a cataclysmic event.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The TV series *The X-Files* cited 22 December 2012 as the date for an alien colonization of the Earth, and mentioned the Mayan calendar "stopping" on this date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The History Channel aired a handful of special series on doomsday that included analysis of 2012 theories, such as *Decoding the Past* (2005–2007), *2012, End of Days* (2006), *Last Days on Earth* (2006), *Seven Signs of the Apocalypse* (2009), and *Nostradamus 2012* (2008).
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The Discovery Channel also aired *2012 Apocalypse* in 2009, suggesting that massive solar storms, magnetic pole reversal, earthquakes, supervolcanoes, and other drastic natural events could occur in 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In 2012, the National Geographic Channel launched a show called *Doomsday Preppers*, a documentary series about survivalists preparing for various cataclysms, including the 2012 doomsday.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Hundreds of books were published on the topic.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The bestselling book of 2009, Dan Brown's *The Lost Symbol*, featured a coded mock email number (2456282.5) that decoded to the Julian date for 21 December 2012.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In the Ubisoft game franchise *Assassin's Creed*, the overarching plotline of the games starring the first protagonist, Desmond Miles, was also inspired by the phenomenon.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] After escaping capture by the Knights Templar, Desmond rejoins the Assassins Brotherhood to help them fight the Templars and prevent the predicted end of the world, in this case caused by a cyclical solar flare.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] As these promotions did not mention the film itself, many viewers believed them to be real and contacted astronomers in panic.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Although the campaign was criticized, the film became one of the most successful of its year, grossing nearly $770 million worldwide.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] An article in *The Daily Telegraph* attributed the widespread fear of the phenomenon in China to the film, which was a hit in the country as it depicted the Chinese building "survival arks".
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Lars von Trier's 2011 film *Melancholia* featured a plot in which a planet emerges from behind the Sun on a collision course with Earth.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon also inspired several rock and pop music hits.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] As early as 1997, "A Certain Shade of Green" by Incubus referred to the mystical belief that a shift in perception would arrive in 2012 ("Are you gonna stand around till 2012 A.D.? / What are you waiting for, a certain shade of green?").
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Towards mid-December 2012, an internet hoax related to South Korean singer Psy being one of the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse was widely circulated around social media platforms.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The hoax purported that once Psy's "Gangnam Style" YouTube video amassed a billion views, the world would end.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] Rahman, known for *Slumdog Millionaire*, released his single "Infinite Love" to "instill faith and optimism in people" prior to the hypothesized doomsday.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The artwork for All Time Low's 2012 album *Don't Panic* satirizes various cataclysmic events associated with the phenomenon.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] The phenomenon was also satirized in Brian M.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] A number of brands ran commercials tied to the phenomenon in the days and months leading to the date.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] In February 2012, American automotive company General Motors aired an advertisement during the annual Super Bowl football game in which a group of friends drove Chevrolet Silverados through the ruins of human civilization following the 2012 apocalypse.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] On 17 December 2012, Jell-O ran an ad saying that offering Jell-O to the Mayan gods would appease them into sparing the world.
[src:extinction/2012-phenomenon] John Verret, Professor of Advertising at Boston University, questioned the utility of tying large sums of money to such a unique and short-term event.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:extinction/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In the 1st century, it was taken up by the authors of the gospels in the context of the Roman destruction of Jerusalem and the Temple in the year 70, with the Gospel of Mark placing the "abomination of desolation" into a speech by Jesus concerning the Second Coming.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Chapters 1–6 of the Book of Daniel originated as a collection of oral literature from Hellenistic Palestine in the late 4th to early 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] At that time, a lamb was sacrificed twice daily, in the morning and the evening, on the altar of the Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In 167 BCE, Antiochus IV Epiphanes, the Seleucid emperor, who then ruled Palestine, ended the practice.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In reaction to this, the visionary chapters of Daniel, chapters 7–12, were added to reassure Jews that they would survive in the face of this threat.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In Daniel 8, one angel asks another how long "the transgression that makes desolate" will last.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] More recently, it has been suggested that the reference is to baetyls, possibly of meteoric origin, that were fixed to the altar of sacrifice for worship, since the use of such stones is well-attested in Canaanite and Syrian cults.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Daniel 11:31, 12:11; 2 Maccabees 6:5), or the pagan altar on which such offerings were made.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In 63 BCE, the Roman Republic captured Jerusalem, Judea became a client state of Rome for the remainder of Hasmonean and later Herodian rule, and eventually became a province of the Roman Empire.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In 66 CE, the Jews rose in revolt in the First Jewish–Roman War.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] The war ended in 70 CE when the legions of the Roman general Titus surrounded and eventually captured Jerusalem; the city and the Temple were razed to the ground, and the only habitation on the site until the first third of the next century was a castrum.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] It was against this background that the gospels were written; the Gospel of Mark around 70 and Matthew and Luke around 80–85.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] The secular scholars believe that none of the authors were eyewitnesses to the life of Jesus, and that Mark was the source used by the authors of Matthew and Luke for their "abomination of desolation" passages.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Chapter 13 of the Gospel of Mark is a speech of Jesus concerning the return of the son of man and the advent of the Kingdom of God, which will be signalled by the appearance of the "abomination of desolation".
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] The majority of scholars believe that Mark was the source used by the authors of Matthew and Luke for their "abomination of desolation" passages.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Luke 21:20–21 drops the "abomination" entirely: "But when you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, then know that its desolation has come near.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains, and let those who are inside the city depart, and let not those who are out in the country enter it." In all three, the authors likely had in mind a future eschatological (i.e., end-time) event, and perhaps the activities of some antichrist.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] It is an expression found in Matthew 24:15 and Mark 13:14 that refers to an *abominable stele* of Daniel 8:13, Daniel 9:27, Daniel 11:31 and Daniel 12:11 (see Prophecy of Seventy Weeks).
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] This expression refers to the transgression of the Law of Moses by the Jews when they were being taken captive to Babylon.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] The graven image mentioned in the Old Testament is called a *stele* by ancient peoples, such as the Egyptians, and were usually funerary tablets that pagan peoples made for their gods.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] God's people were serving stelae (graven images) and serving other pagan gods such as the queen of heaven in the Babylonian captivity.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Both the prophets Daniel and Jesus warned the Israelites of their turning away from God and of the End Times, as in the Prophecy of Seventy Weeks, which is prophesied by the angel Gabriel of the coming of the Anti-Messiah, who after the 62 weeks would come to ravage humanity.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] There is also a meaning in esoteric occult circles, that the stele of Revelation, also known as the stele of Ankh-af-na-Khonsu, would be filled with prophecies of the Anti-Messiah, according to interpretations of the religion developed by Aleister Crowley, called Thelema.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] According to the Bible in II Kings 23:13 and I Kings 11:5 one can find a close link between the concepts of idolatry and abomination.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] In the circles of direct influence of the Book of Daniel, which are the same circles that gave rise to apocalyptic literature, the expression was used to designate an important eschatological conception.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] It is only in an eschatological sense that the expression can be adequately explained in the New Testament passages mentioned above.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] According to some modern commentators, these passages are a “Jewish apocalypse”, which was reinterpreted by Christianity as a prophecy about the end times, when the Antichrist (abomination of desolation), will come to ravage the Earth and its inhabitants.
[src:extinction/abomination-of-desolation] Allen maintains that the evangelists were referring to Caligula's desire to build a statue of himself in the Temple of Jerusalem.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:extinction/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:extinction/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] An **AI takeover** is a theorized future event, often depicted in fiction, in which autonomous artificial intelligence systems acquire the capability to supersede human decisions.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] This could occur through economic manipulation, infrastructure control, or direct intervention, leading to de facto governance.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Scenarios range from gradual economic dominance, as automation supplants the human workforce, up to a sudden or aggressive global takeover by a **robot uprising** or other forms of **rogue AI**.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Stories of AI takeovers have been popular throughout science fiction.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Commentators argue that recent advancements in the field have heightened concern about such scenarios.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] In public debate, prominent figures such as Stephen Hawking have advocated research into precautionary measures to ensure future superintelligent machines remain under human control.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The traditional consensus among economists has been that technological progress does not cause long-term unemployment.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] However, recent innovation in the fields of robotics and artificial intelligence has raised worries that human labor will become obsolete, leaving workers in some sectors without employment.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Many small and medium-sized firms may also be forced to close if they cannot afford or license the latest robotic and AI technology, and may need to focus on areas or services that cannot easily be replaced for continued viability in the face of such technology.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] While these technologies have replaced some traditional workers, they also create new opportunities.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Industries that are most susceptible to AI-driven automation include transportation, retail, and the military.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI military technologies, for example, can reduce risk by enabling remote operation.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] A study in 2024 highlights AI's ability to perform routine and repetitive tasks poses significant risks of job displacement, especially in sectors like manufacturing and administrative support.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Author Dave Bond argues that as AI technologies continue to develop and expand, the relationship between humans and robots will change; they will become closely integrated in several aspects of life.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI will likely displace some workers while creating opportunities for new jobs in other sectors, especially in fields where tasks are repeatable.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The study further finds that job losses are concentrated in roles where AI automates routine tasks, whereas occupations that leverage AI to augment human work have seen stable or increasing employment.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Computer-integrated manufacturing uses computers to control the production process.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] This allows individual processes to exchange information with each other and initiate actions.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Although manufacturing can be faster and less error-prone through the integration of computers, the main advantage is the ability to create automated manufacturing processes.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Computer-integrated manufacturing is used in automotive, aviation, space, and shipbuilding industries.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The 21st century has seen a variety of skilled tasks partially taken over by machines, including translation, legal research, and journalism.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Care work, entertainment, and other tasks requiring empathy, previously thought safe from automation, are increasingly performed by robots and AI systems.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] An autonomous car is a vehicle that is capable of sensing its environment and navigating without human input.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Many such vehicles are operational and others are being developed, with legislation rapidly expanding to allow their use.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Obstacles to widespread adoption of autonomous vehicles have included concerns about the resulting loss of driving-related jobs in the road transport industry, and safety concerns.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] On March 18, 2018, a pedestrian was struck and killed in Tempe, Arizona by an Uber self-driving car.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] In the 2020s, automated content became more relevant due to technological advancements in AI models, such as ChatGPT, DALL-E, and Stable Diffusion.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] In most cases, AI-generated content such as imagery, literature, and music are produced through text prompts.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] These AI models are sometimes integrated into creative programs.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI-generated art may sample and conglomerate existing creative works, producing results that appear similar to human-made content.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Low-quality AI-generated visual artwork can be informally referred to as AI slop.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Some artists use a tool called Nightshade that alters images to make them detrimental to the training of text-to-image models if scraped without permission, while still looking normal to humans.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI-generated images are a potential tool for scammers and those looking to gain followers on social media, either to impersonate a famous individual or group or to monetize their audience.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The New York Times has sued OpenAI, alleging copyright infringement related to the training and outputs of its AI models.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Physicist Stephen Hawking, Microsoft founder Bill Gates, and SpaceX founder Elon Musk have expressed concerns about the possibility that AI could develop to the point that humans could not control it, with Hawking theorizing that this could "spell the end of the human race".
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Stephen Hawking said in 2014 that "Success in creating AI would be the biggest event in human history.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Stephen Hawking expressed confidence that superhuman AI is physically possible, stating "there is no physical law precluding particles from being organised in ways that perform even more advanced computations than the arrangements of particles in human brains".
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] There are debates on how realistic AI takeover scenarios are.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] According to a 2026 research paper, many of the arguments about existential risks are based on speculative assumptions about how intelligent AI systems could become, how they would behave and what goals they might develop over time.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Jürgen Schmidhuber said in 2023 that AI progress is unstoppable anyway, and is often used for beneficial purpose, including against bad actors.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] A 2023 Reuters/Ipsos survey showed that 61% of American adults feared AI could pose a threat to civilization.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI alignment research studies how to design AI systems so that they follow intended objectives.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] AI takeover is a recurring theme in science fiction.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] According to Toby Ord, the idea that an AI takeover requires robots is a misconception driven by the media and Hollywood.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] He argues that the most damaging humans in history were not physically the strongest, but that they used words instead to convince people and gain control of large parts of the world.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The word "robot" from *R.U.R.* comes from the Czech word *robota*, meaning laborer or serf.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] The 1920 play was a protest against the rapid growth of technology, featuring manufactured "robots" with increasing capabilities who eventually revolt.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] HAL 9000 (1968) and the original Terminator (1984) are two iconic examples of hostile AI in pop culture.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Nick Bostrom and others have expressed concern that an AI with the abilities of a competent artificial intelligence researcher would be able to modify its own source code and increase its own intelligence.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] If its self-reprogramming leads to getting even better at being able to reprogram itself, the result could be a recursive intelligence explosion in which it would rapidly leave human intelligence far behind.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Biological neurons operate at about 200 Hz, whereas a modern microprocessor operates at a speed of about 2 GHz.
[src:extinction/ai-takeover] Human axons carry action potentials at around 120 m/s, whereas computer signals travel near the speed of light.
